igm: a model that pathologizes distress and obscures the social, political, and historical contexts that contribute to human suffering. The authors introduce the perspectives of those who have direct personal knowledge of suicide and suicidal behaviour and propose alternative approaches to suicide prevention that are creative, socially just, and culturally responsive. In the right hands, this book could save lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSuicidal behavior. 0aSuicidexPrevention. 0aSuicidexSociological aspects. 0aSuicide. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Suicide.2bisacsh1 aBergmans, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCover, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDineen, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFullagar, Simone, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGone, Joseph P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHjelmeland, Heidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIdlout, Lori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaworski, Katrina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Denise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKral, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKral, Michael J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMarsh, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarsh, Ian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorris, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorris, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNewman, David, econ